    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Abuse of Heroin, All Around</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Cory Franklin letter on Apr 25 article warns of rise in serious asthma and lung disease from snorting heroin</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Face of Heroin: It's Younger and Suburban'' (news article, April 25), Dr. Herbert D. Kleber cites the myth that teenagers believe they can't die or become addicted if they snort heroin, rather than inject it.</p>
        <p>Here in Chicago, there has been an increase in fatal and near fatal asthma associated with snorting heroin. This may be a reaction to the heroin itself or to adulterants in the drug.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Face of Heroin: It's Younger and Suburban'' (news article, April 25), Dr. Herbert D. Kleber cites the myth that teenagers believe they can't die or become addicted if they snort heroin, rather than inject it.</p>
        <p>Here in Chicago, there has been an increase in fatal and near fatal asthma associated with snorting heroin. This may be a reaction to the heroin itself or to adulterants in the drug.</p>
        <p>As the trend of heroin use shifts from injection to snorting, this suggests that the medical consequences of heroin injection -- H.I.V. infection, damage to kidneys, liver and heart -- will shift to an associated increase in serious asthma and lung disease.</p>
        <p>CORY  FRANKLIN , M.D.  Chicago, April 25, 2000</p>
      </block>
